SIMPLE: invidious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invidious
<hw>In*vid"i*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>invidiosus</ets>, fr. <ets>invidia</ets> envy. See <er>Envy</er>,
and cf. <er>Envious</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Envious; malignant.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Worthy of envy; desirable; enviable.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a person appeareth in a far more honorable and
<qex>invidious</qex> state than any prosperous man.</q>
<rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Likely to or intended to incur or produce ill will,
or to provoke envy or resentment; hateful; offensive; <as>as,
<ex>invidious</ex> distinctions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Agamemnon found it an <qex>invidious</qex> affair to give the
preference to any one of the Grecian heroes.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>In*vid"i*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>In*vid"i*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms></p>

<p><ent>Invigilancy</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Invigilance</ent>⟦br⟧
